The Definitive Guide to SQLite (Expert's Voice in Open Source) 2nd Edition, Kindle Edition

by Grant Allen (Author), Mike Owens (Author) Format: Kindle Edition
3.7 3.7 out of 5 stars 29 ratings
3.9 on Goodreads
47 ratings
Part of: Expert's Voice in Open Source (17 books)
See all formats and editions
Sorry, there was a problem loading this page. Try again.

Outside of the world of enterprise computing, there is one database that enables a huge range of software and hardware to flex relational database capabilities, without the baggage and cost of traditional database management systems. That database is SQLitean embeddable database with an amazingly small footprint, yet able to handle databases of enormous size. SQLite comes equipped with an array of powerful features available through a host of programming and development environments. It is supported by languages such as C, Java, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, TCL, and more.

The Definitive Guide to SQLite, Second Edition is devoted to complete coverage of the latest version of this powerful database. It offers a thorough overview of SQLites capabilities and APIs. The book also uses SQLite as the basis for helping newcomers make their first foray into database development. In only a short time you can be writing programs as diverse as a server-side browser plug-in or the next great iPhone or Android application!

  • Learn about SQLite extensions for C, Java, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, and Tcl.
  • Get solid coverage of SQLite internals.
  • Explore developing iOS (iPhone) and Android applications with SQLite.

SQLite is the solution chosen for thousands of products around the world, from mobile phones and GPS devices to set-top boxes and web browsers. You almost certainly use SQLite every day without even realizing it!

About the Author

Grant Allen has worked in the IT field for over 20 years, as a CTO, enterprise architect, and database administrator. Grant's roles have covered private enterprise, academia and the government sector around the world, specialising in global-scale systems design, development, and performance. He is a frequent speaker at industry and academic conferences, on topics ranging from data mining to compliance, and technologies such as databases (DB2, Oracle, SQL Server, MySQL), content management, collaboration, disruptive innovation, and mobile ecosystems like Android. His first Android application was a task list to remind him to finish all his other unfinished Android projects. Grant works for Google, and in his spare time is completing a Ph.D on building innovative high-technology environments. Grant is the author of Beginning DB2, and lead author of Oracle SQL Recipes and The Definitive Guide to SQLite.

Mark
2.0 out of 5 stars Exasperating and sloppy
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on June 2, 2015
Verified Purchase
This is a review of the paperback, 2nd edition of the book.

I'll mention the good points first: This book does contain a lot of information, and the authors seem to have avoided the abomination of trying to be witty and humorous on every page. It isn't the worst computer programming book I've read.

The bad points are, alas, significant:

(*) The print quality. The book was printed by Amazon and every character is surrounded by tiny dots. The text is readable but has an annoying fuzzy haze around it. It looks like each page was stored as an image rather than being stored as raw data.

(*) There aren't many tables in the book but in some of them the data in the columns doesn't line-up under the appropriate column heading. For example, the table on page 167 has three columns but all the text that should be in the second column has been appended to the first column leaving the second column completely empty. The table of binary operators on page 61 is a particularly painful example: It doesn't merely split phrases across columns, but even splits words: "equa" in one column and "l" in the next. Once you get used to this idiotically sloppy formatting and know to expect it, the tables can be understood but it is a sorry and shameful state of affairs.

(*) Some source code examples won't compile, not because of some minor punctuation slip but because they are fundamentally wrong. The very first example I attempted showed a C-language function being called with two arguments ... what a pity then that the function as defined in the library takes four arguments. The function in question was the sqlite3_open_v2 which is presented with two arguments instead of four on pages 156, 157, 163, 168, 184 and 186 -- so the very first function you'll need to use in order to create or read a database is presented incorrectly in every example in which it is to be found.

(*) The organisation of the book is somewhat akin to a series of essays heavily interwoven with examples. It is not an easy format to use for obtaining specific information at a glance, nor for gaining a good overview of a topic. Much of the material in the book is of a kind that I'd have preferred to find in appendices that had a page dedicated to the comprehensive explanation of a single function (or variable, or SQL statement, or ...).

Where tables are provided they don't necessarily contain useful information, as is the case with the list of result codes. This table provides the mnemonic and the description but doesn't inform the reader of the code value -- which is the very thing you will want to look-up. Additionally the table only lists about one-third of the possible mnemonics. Consequently when your function call returns the integer 101 as a result code you'll have to look elsewhere to find out what '101' signifies.

In the arrangement of information used by the book, it is frequently difficult to find a definitive explanation even of simple matters; instead one must rummage back and forth and hope that the topic is wholly covered by the time you've found each morsel. Which brings us to ... the index ...

(*) The index is moderately lengthy but appears to have been generated by a computer program that had no idea of the significance of the context for each term. Consequently one might turn to a suggested page only to find that the term is mentioned merely in passing, without any depth.

Overall then, during about three days of use I've found the book to be an exasperating, sloppily produced and ultimately unimpressive publication. It hasn't been entirely useless but I've had to turn to the source code and to the Internet to gain the clarity and understanding that could and should have been plainly expressed on the printed pages of this book. Is it worth the forty-something quid? Perhaps only if your time is so valuable that its worth paying that much for an executive overview, because when you try to write code you will immediately need reference material that is more reliable, more comprehensive, and more accessible than what is offered by this book.

It may help other prospective purchasers of this book to know that my interest is in the SQLite flavour of SQL commands and in the C-language API. I have no interest in accessing SQLite through Python or C++ or knowing about its use on Android so I've skipped those chapters and cannot comment on them.
